Introduction

Artificial Intelligence (AI) has been rapidly transforming how people live and work, with an increase in popularity in recent years and there is no sign of it stopping anytime soon. With AI shaping how people work and more industries adopting AI, it has become an increasingly concerning question of when or how AI is going to affect the workforce. My group wanted to investigate those concerns with analysis of how AI may impact jobs in the future and see how jobs may be changing, adapting, or getting completely removed with the growing reliance on AI.

Data Acquisition and Cleaning

To find answers to this question, we used the “AI Job Threat Index” from Kaggle 1 and the Employment Projection Dataset publishsed by the U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics2. The first dataset from Kaggle measures AI threat ## Initial AnalysisVisualization

Code 
# Clean and prepare the BLS data
bls_clean <- bls |> 
  select(-`Occupation Code`, -`Median Annual Wage 2023`, -`Education Code`, -`Workex Code`) |> 
  rename(job_title = `Occupation Title`) |> 
  mutate(job_title = str_to_lower(str_trim(job_title)))

# Clean the AI data
ai_clean <- ai |> 
  rename(job_title = `Job titles`) |>  # ✅ FIXED TYPO
  mutate(job_title = str_to_lower(str_trim(job_title)))

# Combine the two datasets using fuzzy matching
combined_data <- stringdist_inner_join(
  ai_clean, bls_clean,
  by = "job_title",
  max_dist = 0.4,
  method = "jw"
)

# Clean up column names
combined_data <- combined_data |> 
  select(-job_title.y) |> 
  rename(job_title = job_title.x)

# Rename columns for clarity
combined_data <- combined_data |>
  select(-trCode) |> 
  rename(
    Job_Title = job_title,
    AI_Impact = `AI Impact`,
    Education_Level = `Typical Entry-Level Education`,
    Job_Training = `Typical on-the-job Training`,
    Employment_Change_2023_2033 = `Employment Change, 2023-2033`,
    Employment_Percent_Change_2023_2033 = `Employment Percent Change, 2023-2033`,
    Work_Experience = `Work Experience in a Related Occupation`,
    Occupational_Openings_Annual_Avg = `Occupational Openings, 2023-2033 Annual Average`
  )

# Capitalize job titles for readability
combined_data$Job_Title <- str_to_title(combined_data$Job_Title)
View(combined_data)
write_csv(combined_data, "data/combined_data.csv")

domains <- unique(combined_data$Domain)
# Build base plot
p <- plot_ly()

# Loop through each domain and add a trace
for (i in seq_along(domains)) {
  domain_data <- combined_data |>
    filter(Domain == domains[i])
  
  p <- p %>%
    add_trace(
      data = domain_data,
      x = ~AI_Workload_Ratio,
      y = ~Employment_Change_2023_2033,
      type = "scatter",
      mode = "markers",
      text = ~paste("Job:", Job_Title),
      name = domains[i],
      visible = ifelse(i == 1, TRUE, FALSE)  # Only first visible by default
    )
}

# Add dropdown buttons
buttons <- lapply(seq_along(domains), function(i) {
  vis <- rep(FALSE, length(domains))
  vis[i] <- TRUE
  list(method = "restyle",
       args = list("visible", vis),
       label = domains[i])
})

# Final layout with dropdown
p <- p %>%
  layout(
    title = "AI Risk vs. Employment Change by Industry",
    xaxis = list(title = "AI Workload Ratio"),
    yaxis = list(title = "Employment Change (2023–2033)"),
    updatemenus = list(
      list(
        type = "dropdown",
        active = 0,
        buttons = buttons,
        direction = "down",
        x = 1.05,
        y = 0.9
      )
    )
  )

p
